    mainEntity: [
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'What does AEO ROI mean?',
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: 'AEO ROI refers to the return on investment generated by Answer Engine Optimisation — the practice of optimising content and entities to earn citations in AI-generated answers. Because AI search does not produce a standard click-through event, ROI is measured through a combination of leading indicators (citation frequency, brand mention accuracy, share of voice across AI platforms) and lagging indicators (branded search uplift, direct traffic, and pipeline attribution from prospects who mention AI search as a discovery channel).'
        }
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'Why is AEO harder to attribute than SEO?',
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: 'AEO is harder to attribute than SEO because the primary value delivery — a user receiving an answer that mentions or recommends your brand — happens inside an AI engine interface with no trackable click or session. The user may act on that mention hours or days later through a direct navigation or branded search, creating a gap between the AI citation event and the observable website interaction. Standard analytics cannot bridge this gap without additional instrumentation such as post-purchase surveys and UTM-tagged AI referral tracking.'
        }
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'What are the leading indicators for AEO ROI?',
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: 'The leading indicators for AEO ROI are: citation frequency (how often your brand appears in AI-generated answers for target queries), citation accuracy (whether the AI describes your brand correctly), share of voice across platforms (your proportion of citations relative to competitors), and prompt coverage (the percentage of your target query set for which you receive at least one citation). These indicators precede revenue impact and signal whether your programme is on a positive trajectory before downstream commercial outcomes are visible.'
        }
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'How do you attribute revenue to AEO activity?',
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: 'Revenue attribution for AEO relies on a combination of methods: tracking branded search volume uplift correlated with citation programme milestones, capturing AI search as a discovery channel in post-purchase CRM surveys, monitoring direct and dark traffic for increases that correlate with AEO activity, and tagging any traffic that arrives via AI platform referral links (where platforms surface them). No single attribution method provides complete coverage — a multi-signal model that triangulates across these sources provides the most defensible picture.'
        }
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'How long before AEO investments produce measurable returns?',
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: 'Leading indicators — citation frequency and prompt coverage — typically show movement within 60 to 90 days of systematic AEO activity. Lagging indicators, including branded search uplift and pipeline contributions, require six to twelve months to accumulate enough signal to isolate from other marketing activity. Entity authority improvements, which underpin long-term citation stability, compound over twelve to twenty-four months. Programmes that expect immediate revenue attribution from AEO will be disappointed; programmes that track leading indicators from month one build a credible ROI narrative progressively.'
        }
      },
      {
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: 'What should an AEO ROI model include?',
        acceptedAnswer: {
          '@type': 'Answer',
          text: 'A defensible AEO ROI model should include: a baseline citation audit (frequency and accuracy before the programme begins), a defined query set representing commercial intent, monthly tracking of leading indicators across at least three AI platforms, a methodology for connecting branded search and direct traffic changes to AEO milestones, and a conservative revenue assumption based on the proportion of AI-influenced pipeline that converts. Avoid fabricating citation-to-conversion rates — use your own historical close rates applied to AI-influenced pipeline estimates derived from survey data.'
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://geooptimised.com/' },
